Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucester, Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"1502–1532":"1502–1532","1502–1545":"1502–1545","1524–Male":"1524–Deceased","1526–1576":"1526–1576","1528–Male":"1528–Deceased","1530–1576":"1530–1576","1527–1561":"1527–1561","1440–1532":"1440–1532","1440–1558":"1440–1558","1440":"1440","1561":"1561","1558":"1558","1502":"1502","1524":"1524","after 1524":"after 1524","1545":"1545","1532":"1532","1576":"1576","1530":"1530","1528":"1528","1527":"1527","1526":"1526","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Gloucester, Glouchestershire, England":"Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England":"Gloucester, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Clay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Midlands and Yorkshire): from Old English <i>clǣg</i> ‘clay’, applied as a topographic name for someone who lived in an area of clay soil, a habitational name for someone who lived in a district known as (the) Clay, such as the one in east Notinghamshire, or as a metonymic occupational name for a worker in a clay pit (see   Clayman  ).","Americanized form of German   Klee  .","History: The relatively common English name Clay had several American forebears in the 18th century. Henry Clay, born in Hanover, VA, in 1777, secretary of state for President John Quincy Adams, was descended from English ancestors who came to VA shortly after the founding of Jamestown. The revolutionary war officer Joseph Clay, also a member of the Continental Congress, was a native of Yorkshire, England, who emigrated to GA in 1760 and was a founder of the University of Georgia."],"variants":[{"name":"Klee","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Ernst, Hans, Hellmut, Helmut, Horst, Kurt, Manfred, Otmar, Otto, Wolfgang.","German: possibly a nickname for a clover farmer, from <i>Klee</i> ‘clover’. Compare   Clay   and   Clee  ."]},{"name":"Clayman","meanings":["English: from Middle English <i>cleymann</i>, from <i>cley</i> ‘clay’ (see   Clay  ) + <i>mann</i> ‘man’, an occupational name for one who prepared clay for use in brick making or pottery, or for a plasterer (see   Clare   3).","Americanized form of German and Jewish (Ashkenazic) <b>Kleimann</b>, or of Jewish   Kleiman  ,   Klayman   ‘small man’."]}]},{"name":"John","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John Thomas Clay I was born in 1502, in Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Thomas Claye, was 62 and his mother, Ann Claye, was 62. He had at least 4 sons with Mary Anne Onthank. He died in 1532, in Derbyshire, England, at the age of 30."},"et":{"1502–1532":"1502–1532","1502–1545":"1502–1545","1524–Male":"1524–Surnud","1526–1576":"1526–1576","1528–Male":"1528–Surnud","1530–1576":"1530–1576","1527–1561":"1527–1561","1440–1532":"1440–1532","1440–1558":"1440–1558","1440":"1440","1561":"1561","1558":"1558","1502":"1502","1524":"1524","after 1524":"pärast 1524","1545":"1545","1532":"1532","1576":"1576","1530":"1530","1528":"1528","1527":"1527","1526":"1526","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Gloucester, Glouchestershire, England":"Gloucester, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England","Gloucester, Gloucestershire